 politician who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|AR|1}} since 2011. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. Before he was elected to Congress, Crawford was a radio announcer, businessman and a soldier in the [[U.S. Army]].\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nCrawford was born in the [[Homestead Air Force Base]] in [[Florida]], the son of Ruth Anne and Donny J. \"Don\" Crawford.<ref>[http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/%7Ebattle/reps/crawford.htm freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com]</ref> Crawford grew up in a military family; his father served in the [[United States Air Force]]. He graduated from [[Alvirne High School]] in [[Hudson, New Hampshire]]. He enlisted in the Army, where he served as an [[Explosive Ordnance Disposal|explosive ordnance disposal technician]] for four years,<ref>{{cite news | first = Andrew | last = Stiles | title = National Review: Turning Arkansas Red | date = 2010-10-27 | url = http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=130855895 | work = [[National Public Radio]] | accessdate = 2010-10-31 }}</ref> and advanced to the rank of [[Sergeant]]. After his service, he attended [[Arkansas State University]] and graduated in 1996 with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.S.]] in Agriculture Business and Economics.\n\n== Radio career ==\nHe has been a [[news anchor]] and agri-reporter on [[KAIT-TV]] in [[Jonesboro, Arkansas|Jonesboro]] and Farm Director on [[KFIN|KFIN-FM]]. He owned and operated the AgWatch Network, a farm news network heard on 39 radio stations in [[Arkansas]], [[Missouri]], [[Tennessee]], [[Mississippi]] and [[Kentucky]].<ref>[http://www.meetrickcrawford.com/about/ meetrickcrawford.com About]</ref>\n\n== U.S. House of Representatives ==\n\n===Elections===\n;2010\n{{Main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Arkansas, 2010#District 1*}}\nCrawford chose to run for [[Arkansas' 1st congressional district]] after Democratic incumbent U.S. Congressman [[Robert Marion Berry|Marion Berry]] decided to retire. Crawford received the endorsements of Minnesota Governor [[Tim Pawlenty]], former Arkansas Governor [[Mike Huckabee]], former Congressman [[Asa Hutchinson]], and former Congressman [[Ed Bethune]].<ref>[http://www.meetrickcrawford.com/endorsements/ meetrickcrawford.com endorsements]</ref> He won the Republican [[Primary election|primary]], defeating [[Princella Smith]] 72%\u201328%.<ref>[http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=572929 www.ourcampaigns.com AR District 01 \u2013 R Primary, 2010]</ref> He won the [[general election]], defeating Berry's chief of staff [[Chad Causey]] 52%\u201343%.<ref>[http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=487762 ourcampaigns.com, AR \u2013 District 01, 2011]</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{Main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Arkansas, 2012#District 1*}}\nCrawford won re-election to a second term, defeating Democratic prosecutor, Scott Ellington, 56%\u201339%.<ref>[http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=705041 ourcampaigns.com, AR \u2013 District 01, 2012]</ref>\n\n;2014\n{{Main article|United States House of Representatives elections in Arkansas, 2014#District 1*}}\nCrawford won re=election to a third term, defeating [[Heber Springs, Arkansas|Heber Springs]] Mayor Jackie McPherson 63%-33%.<ref>http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/AR/53237/149792/Web01/en/summary.html</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nCrawford was sworn into office on January 5, 2011, as a member of the [[112th United States Congress|112th Congress]]. He is the first Republican to represent his district in Washington since [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]]. The last Republican to represent the district was [[Asa Hodges]] who departed the seat on March 3, 1875.<ref>[http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=H000671 bioguide.congress.gov Asa Hodges]</ref> Crawford is a member of the [[Republican Study Committee]].<ref>[http://www.mcallennow.com/voter-resources/official/283914/Rick/Crawford mcallennow.com voter resources, Rick Crawford]</ref>\n\nCrawford voted to repeal the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] and to return federal non-security spending to fiscal year 2008 levels.  He also voted to terminate taxpayer financing of presidential election campaigns and party conventions.<ref>[http://crawford.house.gov/voterecord/ crawford.house.gov vote record]</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Crawford signed a pledge sponsored by [[Americans for Prosperity]] promising to vote against any [[Politics of global warming|Global Warming legislation]] that would raise taxes.<ref>[http://americansforprosperity.org/noclimatetax//wp-content/uploads/2010/04/crawford-rick.pdf /americansforprosperity.org Americans for Prosperity Applauds  U.S. House  Candidate Rick Crawford]</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nOn January 18, 2013, Crawford introduced the [[Farmers Undertake Environmental Land Stewardship Act (H.R. 311; 113th Congress)]] into the House.<ref name=311sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 311 \u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/311|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref> The bill would require the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] (EPA) to modify the Spill Prevention, Control, and Countermeasure (SPCC) rule, which regulates oil discharges into navigable waters and adjoining shorelines.<ref name=cbo311>{{cite web|title=H.R. 311 \u2013 CBO|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/44719|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=10 March 2014}}</ref> The rule requires certain farmers to develop an [[oil spill]] prevention plan that is certified by a professional [[engineer]] and may require them to make [[infrastructure]] changes.<ref name=\"cbo311\"/> According to supporters, this bill would \"ease the burden placed on farmers and ranchers\" by making it easier for smaller farms to self-certify and raising the level of storage capacity under which farms are exempted.<ref name=HighPlainsJ1>{{cite news|title=Committee passes legislation to ease burden of SPCC program|url=http://www.hpj.com/archives/2013/dec13/dec23/1104FUELSActsr.cfm|accessdate=11 March 2014|newspaper=High Plains Journal|date=23 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n[[File:U.S. Congressman Rick Crawford (R-AR) questions Agriculture Secretary Tom Vilsack in 2013.jpg|thumb|Congressman Crawford questions Agriculture Secretary Tom Vilsack in 2013]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Department Operations, Oversight, and Credit|Subcommittee on Department Operations, Oversight, and Credit]]\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management|Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management]]\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Nutrition and Horticulture|Subcommittee on Nutrition and Horticulture]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]]'''\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings and Emergency Management|Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings and Emergency Management]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment|Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]]\n* [[Republican Study Committee]]\n\n==Personal life==\nCrawford and his wife, Stacy, live in [[Jonesboro, Arkansas|Jonesboro]] with their children. He attends Nettleton Baptist Church, a [[Southern Baptist]] church in Jonesboro.<ref>{{cite news |author=Staff |title=Ten Southern Baptists sworn in as new reps. |url=http://www.bpnews.net/bpnews.asp?id=34378 |accessdate=25 December 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226010629/http://www.bpnews.net/34378 |archivedate=25 December 2014 |newspaper=Baptist Press |date=5 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Arkansas 1st Congressional District Republican Primary Election, 2010\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Rick Crawford'''\n|14,461\n|71.79\n|-\n|Republican\n|Princella Smith\n|5,682\n|28.21\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Arkansas 1st Congressional District Election, 2010\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Rick Crawford'''\n|93,224\n|51.79\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Chad Causey\n|78,267\n|43.48\n|-\n|Green\n|Ken Adler\n|8,320\n|4.62\n|-\n|Write-ins\n|Write-ins\n|205\n|0.11\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Arkansas 1st Congressional District Election, 2012\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Rick Crawford (inc.)'''\n|138,800\n|56.23\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Scott Ellington\n|96,601\n|39.13\n|-\n|Libertarian\n|Jessica Paxton\n|6,427\n|2.60\n|-\n|Green\n|Jacob Holloway\n|5,015\n|2.03\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Arkansas 1st Congressional District Election, 2014\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Rick Crawford (inc.)'''\n|124,139\n|63.25\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Jackie McPherson\n|63,555\n|32.38\n|-\n|Libertarian\n|Brian Scott Willhite\n|8,562\n|4.36\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://crawford.house.gov/ Congressman Rick Crawford] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.meetrickcrawford.com/ Rick Crawford for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Arkansas/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Rick_Crawford_%5BR-1%5D|Rick Crawford}}\n* {{C-SPAN|rickcrawford03}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = C001087 | ballot = Rick_Crawford | nndb = 542/000257768